EEGLAB-ready derivatives — jungle vs. deconstruct soundscape segments
=====================================================================

WHAT THIS FOLDER IS
-------------------
A convenience layer for EEGLAB / MATLAB users. The raw dataset (repository root)
stores each participant's recording as ONE combined EDF containing the resting
baseline (eyes-open, eyes-closed) and both ~17 s soundscape exposures, with the
segments marked in the root *_events.tsv. EEGLAB's STUDY designer does not read
within-file segments as conditions, so here the two soundscape conditions are
pre-split into EEGLAB-native .set files that import directly with conditions intact.

Users of MNE-Python or other tools should ignore this folder and use the RAW data
at the repository root (combined EDF + events.tsv), reconstructing conditions as
they wish. The raw root is the canonical dataset; these derivatives are optional.

WHAT IS HERE
------------
  sub-NN/eeg/sub-NN_task-soundscape_acq-jungle_eeg.set
  sub-NN/eeg/sub-NN_task-soundscape_acq-deconstruct_eeg.set
  study_plots_NOPATHS.m          <- copy-paste analysis/plotting script
  dataset_description.json

IMPORTANT: both .set files per participant share the SAME task ('soundscape').
The jungle/deconstruct distinction is carried ONLY by the BIDS 'acq-' label and
the EEG.condition field inside each file. This makes 'condition' the single
categorical STUDY variable (levels: jungle, deconstruct). There is NO 'task'
design variable — do not add one.

The analysis unit is the WHOLE ~17 s segment per condition (1 'trial' per .set),
average reference, raw + 0.5 Hz high-pass (inherited from the raw release).
Baselines (eyes-open/closed) are intentionally excluded here (not part of the
jungle-vs-deconstruct design); they remain in the raw combined EDFs at the root.

=====================================================================
QUICK PATH (recommended) — load as a STUDY, then run the script
=====================================================================
1. Start EEGLAB in MATLAB:   >> eeglab
2. File > Import data > Using EEGLAB functions and plugins > From BIDS folder,
   OR File > Load existing dataset(s) and select all the .set files in this folder.
   (Either way, the datasets load into ALLEEG.)
3. (Optional) File > Create study using all loaded datasets, so EEGLAB reads the
   'condition' and 'subject' fields automatically.
4. Copy the ENTIRE contents of study_plots_NOPATHS.m and paste into the MATLAB
   Command Window. It operates on whatever is in memory (ALLEEG) — NO file paths
   needed — and produces:
       Figure 1 : Jungle alpha topoplot
       Figure 2 : Deconstruct alpha topoplot (same colour scale)
       Figure 3 : Grand-average spectra overlay (jungle vs deconstruct)
       Figure 4 : Descriptives table — relative band power %, mean (SE), all 5 bands
   To view a different band, change PLOT_BAND at the top of the script
   (delta / theta / alpha / beta / gamma) and re-run.

=====================================================================
BUILDING A STUDY DESIGN BY HAND (if you prefer the GUI)
=====================================================================
1. Load all .set files (step 2 above).
2. Study > Edit study design > Add variable:
       Independent variable 1 = 'condition'  (Categorical)
       values: deconstruct, jungle
       Leave the second variable as 'None'.  (This is the ONLY design variable.)
3. Study > Precompute channel measures > Power spectrum (spec).
4. Study > Plot channel measures > Spectra, with "plot condition difference" on.
5. Statistics (within-subject): Study > statistics > paired, on the variable
   'condition' (jungle vs deconstruct).

NOTES
-----
- topoplot needs channel coordinates; the script fills them via EEGLAB's standard
  montage lookup automatically. If it can't find the montage file, do
  Edit > Channel locations > "Look up locs" once in the GUI, then re-run.
- For publication-grade figures, MNE-Python's topographies look nicer; EEGLAB here
  is for convenient analysis. Either tool reads the same underlying data.
- Requires the Signal Processing Toolbox (pwelch) for the script.
